collections.name: Scarabverse
collections.description: The scarab beetle, especially the sacred scarab, holds powerful symbolism in various cultures, such as the Egyptian. It is often associated with the sun, renewal, and protection. The scarab symbolizes resurrection and transformation, due to its behavior of rolling dung balls, which were seen as a process of renewal and creation. In Egyptian mythology, the god Khepri, linked to the rising sun, is often depicted as a scarab, symbolizing the cycle of life, death, and rebirth. More broadly, the scarab represents the ability to overcome difficulties and regeneration.

collections.name: TRANSPARENCY FILM by MIROSLAW ROGALA
collections.description:
The RHYTHMS TRANSPARENCY FILM Collection tokenizes 9 original computer plotter color drawings by Miroslaw Rogala, printed on transparency film in 1982. These works were created using an early CAD program, likely AutoCAD, where users input commands like "PLN" (plan) or "RCT" (rectangle) to generate precise drawings.

Architects used transparency films to overlay sketches and explore different design layers. In 1982, Rogala accessed a Hewlett Packard computer in a Chicago architectural office, experimenting with drawing modes and a handheld device to create freeform shapes. He intentionally introduced random disorder to symbolize Chicago’s towers, landscapes, and vitality, blending order and chaos in his compositions.

collections.name: FragMints
collections.description:
FragMints is building a community of artist to help end war and build peace.

https://www.fragmints.org

Pop a mint, have a conversation, and help bring peace into the world. 

In the 1960’s  a wave of artists came together around a shared goal of denouncing the establishment’s unwavering support of armed conflict and destabilization of foreign regimes for their own interest.

In the 2020’s art has lost it's quasi prophetic voice speaking about problems in the world. FragMints is about artistic retrograde; the going backwards to rediscover the lost potency of artists in society.



FragMints is driven by peace. We want to invite artists to share a platform that condemns war. FragMints believes if people just popped a breath mint and had more conversations, perhaps we would throw less frag grenades… 

We want to empower peace-fueled and peace-filled conversations, art, and content, and document them, share them, and change the world.
